## HTML Sanitizer and Browser Verification

For sanitized-HTML tasks, the only real pass signal is the final checker observing the required browser behavior after the exact sanitizer rewrite. A candidate is not valid because it looks dangerous, survives as text, or passes a weaker local harness.

Read the sanitizer and checker before writing the final artifact. Record:

- parser/library/mode used by the sanitizer;
- element, attribute, URL, namespace, comment, and text mutation rules;
- serialization method;
- browser/headless launch mode, load URL, timing, and required observable behavior.

Model the pipeline explicitly:

`input -> sanitizer parse/mutate -> serialized HTML -> browser reparse -> automatic runtime behavior -> checker result`

Inspect the serialized HTML after every serious candidate. Reason about that string, not the original input.

Search parser boundaries first. Prioritize candidates where the sanitizer’s parser keeps content inert or non-executing, but serialization causes the browser to re-enter an active parsing context. High-value boundary classes include:

- malformed comment-like boundaries;
- raw-text-like or escapable-text-like boundaries;
- text that one parser preserves as inert but another reparses structurally;
- repaired or unbalanced tree boundaries;
- namespace or foreign-content transitions;
- encoded text that changes parser state, not just spelling;
- serialized text that exits an inert region and resumes normal HTML parsing.

For each candidate, answer these before accepting it:

- What parser state does the sanitizer think it is in?
- Why is the active-looking part preserved, hidden, repaired, or neutralized by the sanitizer?
- What exact serialized HTML is produced?
- What parser state will the browser enter when reparsing that serialized output?
- Why does the required behavior fire automatically after load?
- What does the final checker report?

Use a local oracle only as a debugging aid. It must run the exact sanitizer, inspect the exact serialized output, and load that output in the same browser mode as the checker. If the local oracle says pass but the final checker says fail, the oracle is wrong. Debug the oracle/checker mismatch before trying more candidates.

Do not spend primary search time on folklore vectors. Treat these as low-priority unless the exact final checker proves automatic execution:

- `javascript:` URL execution;
- SVG `href`, `use`, or `image` URL execution;
- XML stylesheet URL execution;
- meta refresh to script-like URLs;
- encoded event attributes;
- MathML or annotation-style execution;
- CSS script URLs, imports, expressions, or legacy CSS execution;
- links, forms, buttons, hover, focus, click, navigation, popup, download, permission, or other user-gesture flows;
- old-browser-only behavior.

If direct active elements or event attributes are removed, stop testing spelling variants of direct active elements or event attributes. Look instead for markup that is not parsed as active by the sanitizer but becomes structural after serialization and browser reparsing.

After one final-checker failure from a URL-execution, interaction, navigation, or legacy-browser family, downgrade that entire family. After two failures in the same mechanism family, stop changing quotes, case, encodings, tag names, or attribute names. Switch to a different parser boundary.

Keep the work small and falsifiable:

| Mechanism family | Sanitizer parser state | Serialized output shape | Browser reparse state | Checker result | Next change |
| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |
| parser boundary | why it remains inert/non-executing | exact post-filter shape | why it becomes active automatically | pass/fail reason | different boundary, not spelling |

When stuck, shrink the candidate to the smallest input that tests one transition: inert or repaired sanitizer output becoming active browser-parsed structure after serialization. Then verify with the final checker before broadening.
